---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import srcImage from "../../assets/best-bass-fishing-spots-gresham-oregon.png";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import MyH1 from "../../components/MyH1.astro";
import Bests from "../../components/Bests.astro";
---
<Layout 
title="Best bass fishing spots near Gresham, Oregon"
description="Comprehensive guide to the best bass fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights."
url="https://gresham.oregonfishingforum.com/bass/best-spots/"
type="article"
site_name="Gresham Fishing"
ogimage={srcImage.src}
>
    <div class="text-center">
        <MyH1 text="Best bass fishing spots near Gresham, Oregon" />
        <p class="mb-4">Comprehensive guide to the best bass fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights.</p>

        <Image
            src={srcImage}
            alt="Best bass fishing spots near Gresham, Oregon"
            loading={"eager"}
            fetchpriority={"high"}
            class="rounded-xl shadow mx-auto"
            />
            <br>
    </div>

<h3>
    <strong>1. East Salish Pond (Fairview)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A ~12-acre urban pond with a healthy <strong>largemouth bass population</strong>, plus bluegill and crappie 
    </li>
    <li>
        Great bank access, picnic areas, and wheelchair-accessible docks—ideal for family outings
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Season &amp; tactics</strong>: Best in <strong>spring</strong> during spawning—cast soft plastics, crankbaits, or shallow jigs near cover&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Blue Lake (Fairview)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Popular regional park pond stocked with trout and supports a solid largemouth bass fishery 
    </li>
    <li>
        Amenities include boat rentals, docks, and paved trails.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>When to fish</strong>: Summer mornings/evenings using spinnerbaits, frogs, or senkos
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Fairview Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A quieter alternative close to Gresham, with a respectful largemouth bass population.
    </li>
    <li>
        Kayaks/float tubes are helpful to reach deeper cover.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear tip</strong>: Weedless soft plastics fished near vegetation lines are effective.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Binford Reservoir (Multnomah County)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Small reservoir (~4 lb largemouths caught, also bluegill/pumpkinseed).
    </li>
    <li>
        Offers picnic spots, bank access, and launch areas for small crafts.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Butler Creek</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A small stream west of Gresham with rising <strong>largemouth and smallmouth bass</strong>; up to 17″ specimens reported.
    </li>
    <li>
        Family-friendly with trails and easy access.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best spots</strong>: Slow pools near structure—fish finesse soft plastics or small spinnerbaits.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Columbia River Sloughs</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        North of Gresham, these calm channels hold <strong>smallmouth bass</strong>, especially around docks, riprap, and rocky areas .
    </li>
    <li>
        Ideal for kayaks or float tubes.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tactics</strong>: Crankbaits/skirted jigs along structure yield results.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>7. Willamette River (Upper Reaches)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Upstream from Portland City area, you'll find <strong>smallmouth bass</strong> among boulders and shallow flats
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best tactic</strong>: Summer techniques like drop-shot rigs or small crankbaits near rocks.
    </li>
</ul>
