    Spring and fall are peak seasons, but winter finesse can still produce
</p>
<h2>
    Gear &amp; Tactics
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rods</strong>: 6’6″–7′ medium-heavy spinning or baitcasting.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line</strong>: 10–20 lb braid or mono.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tackle</strong>:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Topwater</strong>: frogs/poppers in warm, vegetated waters.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Soft plastics</strong>: Texas- or wacky-rigged Senkos or creature baits.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Crankbaits</strong> &amp; <strong>spinnerbaits</strong>: around structure and in open water.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Color Guide</strong>: Stained water → green pumpkin/black-blue. Clear water → natural shad/brown
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Licenses &amp; Regulations
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon Angling License</strong> required for ages 12 and over.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bass bag limit</strong>: generally 5 fish/day (check local ODFW rules).
    </li>
    <li>
        Special regs may apply to wild bass in creeks—catch &amp; release enforced until late spring&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Bonus Nearby Bass Lakes
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Hartman Pond</strong> (Benson State Park): 23 acre pond near Multnomah Falls with bass, crappie, and stocked trout—good bank/float-tube fishery 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>St. Louis Ponds</strong> (15 mi south): ODFW-managed complex with bass, panfish, and catfish—all bank access with docks &amp; trails 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Henry Hagg Lake</strong> (~45 min away): renowned for giant smallmouth (state records), trophy bass and trout
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Final Thoughts
</h2>
<p>
    Gresham and its surrounding area offer diverse bass fishing opportunities—from urban ponds like East Salish and Blue Lake to wild creek and slough environments. Whether you're shore-bound or in a kayak, you’ll find largemouth and smallmouth action year‑round. Just grab your license, choose the right gear for the season, and hit the water—your next big catch awaits!
</p>

<Bests bestFor="bass" />
</Layout>